    "slides": [
        {
            "id": "s_l3_1",
            "type": "text",
            "title": "A Better Way ✨",
            "content": "A **Promise** is an object that represents a task that will complete... eventually.\n\nIt can be:\n1. **Pending** (working...)\n2. **Fulfilled** (Success! ✅)\n3. **Rejected** (Error! ❌)"
        },
        {
            "id": "s_l3_2",
            "type": "quiz",
            "title": "Quick Check 🧠",
            "content": "",
            "quizData": {
                "id": "q_l3_1",
                "type": "multiple_choice",
                "question": "What state means success?",
                "options": [
                    {
                        "id": "opt1",
                        "text": "Pending",
                        "isCorrect": false
                    },
                    {
                        "id": "opt2",
                        "text": "Rejected",
                        "isCorrect": false
                    },
                    {
                        "id": "opt3",
                        "text": "Fulfilled",
                        "isCorrect": true
                    }
                ],
                "explanation": "Fulfilled means the promise kept its word."
            }
        },
        {
            "id": "s_l3_3",
            "type": "code",
            "title": "Then what? 🤔",
            "content": "When a Promise finishes, we use `.then()` for success and `.catch()` for errors.",
            "codeSnippet": "let myPromise = new Promise(...);\n\nmyPromise\n  .then(function(result) {\n    console.log('Got result: ' + result);\n  })\n  .catch(function(error) {\n    console.log('Oops: ' + error);\n  });",
            "codeLanguage": "javascript",
            "canRunCode": false
        },
        {
            "id": "s_l3_4",
            "type": "text",
            "title": "Chaining 🔗",
            "content": "The cool thing is you can chain them.\n\n`doTask1().then(doTask2).then(doTask3)`\n\nMuch cleaner than callbacks!"
        },
